definition.value: A 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate(4-) arising from deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of 2'-deoxycytidine 5'-triphosphate (dCTP); major species at pH 7.3.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of N(2)-acetyl-L-lysine; major species at pH 7.3.
A ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion arising from global deprotonation of the  triphosphate groups of any nucleoside triphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A 2'-deoxyribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion being the tetraanion formed by global deprotonation of the triphosphate group.
An organophosphate anion resulting from deprotonation of at least one of the acidic hydroxy groups from the triphosphate moiety of a 2'-deoxyribonucleoside triphosphate.
Any cyclitol having one or more alcoholic hydroxy groups replaced by substituted or unsubstituted amino groups.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a fatty acid.
A cyclodepsipeptide antibiotic, which is isolated from the filamentous fungus Aureobasidium pullulans R106 and is toxic to yeast at low concentrations (0.1-0.5 ug/ml).
A monosaccharide derivative consisting of D-galactose having a 1-carboxyethylidene group masking the 4-and 6-positions.
A triterpene glycoside and hemiacetal isolated from a fermentation of Hormonema sp. and which specifically inhibits glucan synthesis in fungal cells.
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of inositol phosphorylceramide synthase.
A terpenoid in which one or more hydroxy functions are glycosylated.
A terpene glycoside in which the terpene moiety is a triterpenoid.
A fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any hydroxy fatty acid.

An EC 1.14.13.* (oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, incorporating 1 atom of oxygen, with NADH or NADPH as one donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of nitric oxide synthase (EC 1.14.13.39).
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to inhibit polymerisation of microtubules.
The (S)-enantiomer of azetidine-2-carboxylic acid.
Zwitterionic form of a polar amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
Any donor that can transfer acyl groups between molecular entities.
A butanediol in which hydroxylation is at C-2 and C-3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of nalidixic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An alkanesulfonate in which the carbon at position 1 is attached to at least two hydrogens.
The organophosphate oxoanion that is the dianion formed from the phosphatidylglycerol cardiolipin by loss of an electron from each of the phospho groups.
An EC 2.7.10.* (protein-tyrosine kinase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of receptor protein-tyrosine kinase (EC 2.7.10.1).

A molecular messenger in which the molecule is specifically involved in transmitting information between cells. Such molecules are released from the cell sending the signal, cross over the gap between cells by diffusion, and interact with specific receptors in another cell, triggering a response in that cell by activating a series of enzyme controlled reactions which lead to changes inside the cell.
Any branched-chain fatty acid containing methyl branches only.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any hydroxycarboxylic acid.
Any organophosphate oxoanion that is a negatively charged phospholipid, e.g. phosphatidylserine(1-), phosphatidate(2-), phosphatidylglycerol(1-).
An ester where the ester linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.
An amide in which the amide linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.
A 2-acylglycerophosphoinositol in which sn-glycerol, acylated at O(2), is linked through a phospho group at O(3) to O(1) of D-myo-inositol.
A glycerophosphoinositol acylated at O(2) of the glycerol moiety.

A family of nitrogen molecular entities which are highly reactive and derived from nitric oxide (.NO) and superoxide (O2.(-)) produced via the enzymatic activity of inducible nitric oxide synthase 2 (NOS2) and NADPH oxidase respectively.
Any additive that enhances the efficiency of fuel.
Any compound that is able to prevent damage to the liver.
An EC 1.2.3.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor aldehyde/oxo group with oxygen as acceptor) inhibitor which interferes with the action of aldehyde oxidase (EC 1.2.3.1).
An EC 2.4.2.* (pentosyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of a NAD(+) ADP-ribosyltransferase (EC 2.4.2.30).
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of mycophenolic acid.
A ceramide compound formed by the replacement of the glycosidic hydroxy group of a cyclic form of a monosaccharide (or derivative) by a ceramide group.
An alpha-amino-acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of homoserine.
The inorganic nitrate salt of potassium.
The chemical role played by a substance that stabilizes an emulsion by increasing its kinetic stability.
An organic cation resulting from protonation or quaternisation at the 3-position of any 1,3-thiazole.
An aluminium atom having a positive net electric charge.
A transition element cation where the metal is specifed as cadmium.
A beta-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of beta-alanine.
A tetracarboxylic acid anion formed by deprotonation of three of the four carboxy groups in ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA).
An EC 1.1.3.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-OH group, oxygen as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of alcohol oxidase (EC 1.1.3.13).
An EC 4.2.1.* (hydro-lyases) inhibitor that interferes with the action of cystathionine beta-synthase (EC 4.2.1.22).
